[[File:Stag Inn, All Saints Street, Hastings - Mummified Cats.JPG|thumb|400px|Dried cats and rats from the Stag Inn, All Saints Street, Hastings.]]
It is the custom in some European cultures to place the dried or desiccated body of a [[cat]] inside the walls of a newly built home to ward off evil spirits or as a [[good luck charm]]. It was believed that the cats had a sixth sense and would have psychic abilities in the afterlife to find the spirits. Putting the cat in the wall was seen as a blood sacrifice to ward off the evil spirits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.apotropaios.co.uk/dried-cats.html|title=Dried Cats|website=Apotropaios|language=en|access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref> Although some accounts claim the cats were walled in alive, examination of recovered specimens indicates post-mortem concealment in most cases.

==Origins==
In the British Isles,<ref>{{citation |last=Merrifield |first=Ralph |title=[[The Archaeology of Ritual and Magic]] |year=1987 |publisher=Batsford |isbn=978-0-7134-4870-2}}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Hoggard |first=Brian |contribution=The archaeology of counter-witchcraft and popular magic |title=Beyond the Witchtrials: Witchcraft and Magic in Enlightenment Europe |editor1-last=Davies |editor1-first=Owen |editor2-last=De Blécourt  |editor2-first=William |year=2004 |publisher=Manchester University Press |isbn=978-0-7190-6660-3}}</ref> as well as in northern Europe and North America,<ref>{{citation |last=Manning |first=M. Chris |title=Homemade Magic: Concealed Deposits in Architectural Contexts in the Eastern United States |year=2012}}</ref> the dried or mummified bodies of cats are frequently found concealed within structures and are believed to have been placed there to bring good luck or to protect the building and its occupants from harm. In some cases, the animals are found deliberately posed as if in the midst of attack.<ref>{{citation |last=Howard |first=Margaret M. |year=1951 |title=252. Dried Cats |journal=Man |volume=51 |publisher=Wiley, Royal Anthropological Institute of Great Britain and Ireland |doi=10.2307/2794702}}</ref> In other cases, they are accompanied by dried rats, mice, or birds.

==Mummification of Cats in Ancient Egypt==
Cats in ancient Egypt were valued very highly and were seen to be very close to the gods. They believed the cats were an embodiment of the goddess [[Bastet]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancientegyptonline.co.uk/cat.html|title=Ancient Egypt Online: Cats in Ancient Egypt|website=www.ancientegyptonline.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-05-10}}</ref>  Harming a cat in ancient Egypt was an offense punishable by death. When a cat died the Egyptians would mummify and bury their cats as an offering to the gods.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thevintagenews.com/2017/11/26/in-ancient-egypt-cats-were-mummified-buried-with-jewelry/|title=In Ancient Egypt, cats were mummified and buried with jewelry, and harming a cat was an offense that could be punished with death|date=2017-11-26|work=The Vintage News|access-date=2018-05-10|language=en-US}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=May 2018}}

