{{more citations needed|reason=Mostly this article cites creationist sources. Could use more mainstream citation.|date=July 2016}}
'''Dr John R. Baumgardner''' is an American [[young earth creationist]] and [[geophysicist]].<ref name= "Moore 2010">{{cite book |title= Chronology of the Evolution-creationism Controversy |first1= Randy |last1= Moore |first2= Mark |last2= Decker |first3= Sehoya |last3= Cotner |year= 2010 |page= [https://books.google.com/books?id=TAPblF5pHDUC&pg=PA321 321] |publisher= [[ABC-CLIO]] |isbn= 9780313362873}}</ref><ref name="newsweek">{{cite news |first=Sharon |last= Begley |magazine= [[Newsweek]] |volume= 128 |issue= 1-14 |page= 82 |url=http://www.newsweek.com/heretics-laboratory-177630 |title=Heretics in the Laboratory|date=September 15, 1996|ref=harv}}</ref>
==Biography== Baumgardner earned a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] from [[Texas Tech University]] in 1968, a [[Master of Science|M.S.]] from Princeton University in 1970, and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in geophysics and space physics from the [[University of California at Los Angeles]] in 1983.<ref name="USNews"/><ref>{{Cite thesis |last=Baumgardner |first=John Rudolph |title=A three-dimensional finite element model for mantle convection |date=1983 |degree=Ph.D. |publisher=[[University of California, Los Angeles]] |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/three-dimensional-finite-element-model-for-mantle-convection/oclc/753781044&referer=brief_results |place=Los Angeles, Cal. |language=English}}</ref> He worked at the [[Los Alamos National Laboratory]] and in 2002 joined the staff of the [[Institute for Creation Research]].<ref name= "Moore 2010"/><ref>{{cite web |title= The Epiphany Project |url= http://www.icr.org/research/epiphany/ |website= icr.org |publisher= [[Institute for Creation Research]] |accessdate= 1 May 2014}}</ref> As a professional scientist, Baumgardner is known for developing TERRA, a [[finite element]] code designed to solve problems in [[mantle convection]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Three-dimensional treatment of convective flow in the earth's mantle |last=Baumgardner |first=John R. |date=1985 |journal=Journal of Statistical Physics |volume=39 |number=5 |pages=501–511 |quote=Cited in 190 references|bibcode=1985JSP....39..501B |doi=10.1007/BF01008348 }}</ref> In 1994 he presented research at a geophysics conference stating that the slip-sliding geologic plates that cover the Earth might once have moved thousands of times faster than they do today.<ref name="newsweek" /> In 1997, ''[[US News and World Report]]'' described him as "the world's pre-eminent expert in the design of computer models for geophysical convection".<ref name="USNews"/>
Baumgardner is a [[Christian]] who sometimes pursues [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] creationist research. He has, for example, created a computer simulation called ''Terra'' to model the [[Noachian flood]].<ref name= "Moore 2010"/><ref name="USNews">{{cite news |url= https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/970616/archive_007221.htm |title= The Geophysics of God: A scientist embraces plate tectonics--and Noah's flood |last= Burr |first= Chandler |authorlink= Chandler Burr |magazine= [[U.S. News & World Report]] |date= 8 June 1997 |pages= 55–8 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070810091759/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/970616/archive_007221.htm |archivedate= 10 August 2007}}</ref>
In 1985, Baumgardner joined the controversial amateur archaeologist [[Ron Wyatt]] and salvage expert [[David Fasold]] to [[Durupınar site|Durupınar, Turkey]] for an expedition recounted in Fasold's ''The Ark of Noah'' to locate the biblical ship's remains.<ref>{{cite book |last= Fasold |first= David |authorlink= David Fasold |title= The Ark of Noah |location= New York |publisher= Wynwood |year= 1988 |page= 7 |isbn= 9780922066100}}</ref> Baumgardner did not support Wyatt's and Fasold's claims to have found a boat-shaped 'object' which was the Ark. He argued that the object was a natural formation.<ref>{{cite web |last= Baumgardner |first= John |title= Letter From John Baumgardner: Regarding the claims of Ron Wyatt |url= http://www.tentmaker.org/WAR/BaumgardnerLetter.html |website= tentmaker.org |date= 26 September 1996 |accessdate= 1 May 2014 |publisher= Tentmaker Ministries |location= Hermann, MO}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date= September 1992 |magazine= Creation Magazine |volume= 14 |issue= 4 |title= Amazing ark expose}}<!-- full citation would be useful, was that the title of the issue or an article page for fact? --></ref>
==Select publications== According to [[Web of Science]], he has published 20 peer-reviewed papers, including: *{{cite journal |last= Baumgardner |first= John R. |title= Three-dimensional treatment of convective flow in the earth's mantle |journal= [[Journal of Statistical Physics]] |volume= 39 |issue= 5–6 |pages= 501–11 |doi= 10.1007/BF01008348 |date= 1 June 1985|bibcode = 1985JSP....39..501B }} cited 75 times. *{{cite journal |last1= Bunge |first1= H.P. |last2= Richards |first2= M.A. |last3= Baumgardner |first3= J.R. |title= Effect of depth-dependent viscosity on the planform of mantle convection |journal= [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] |volume= 379 |issue= 6564 |pages= 436–8 |date= 1 February 1996 |department= Letters to Nature |doi= 10.1038/379436a0 |url= http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v379/n6564/abs/379436a0.html|bibcode = 1996Natur.379..436B }} cited 89 times *{{cite journal |last1= Bunge |first1= Hans-Peter |last2= Richards |first2= Mark A. |last3= Baumgardner |first3= John R. |title= A sensitivity study of three-dimensional spherical mantle convection at 10<sup>8</sup> Rayleigh number: Effects of depth-dependent viscosity, heating mode, and an endothermic phase change |journal= [[Journal of Geophysical Research]] |volume= 102 |issue= B6 |pages= 11991–2007 |date= 10 June 1997 |doi= 10.1029/96JB03806|bibcode = 1997JGR...10211991B }} cited 65 times. *{{cite journal |last1= Sanford |first1= J.C. |last2= Baumgardner |first2= J. |last3= Brewer |first3= W. |last4= Gibson |first4= P. |last5= ReMine |first5= W. |displayauthors= 4 |year= 2007 |title= Mendel's Accountant: A biologically realistic forward-time population genetics program |journal= Scalable Computing: Practice and Experience |volume= 8 |issue= 2 |pages= 147–65 |url= http://www.scpe.org/index.php/scpe/article/view/407/77}}
