[[File:Resin Canals.png|thumb|Resin canals seen as white dots in pine tree viewed under a microscope]] [[File:Axialer Harzkanal Picea abies.jpg|thumb|Axial resin canal (''[[Picea abies]]'')]] [[File:Pinus; leaf (3 needle type) Resin Canal.jpg|thumb|Pinus; leaf (3 needle type) Resin Canal]] '''Resin canals''' or '''resin ducts''' are elongated, tube-shaped intercellular spaces surrounded by [[Epithelium|epithelial cells]] which secrete [[resin]] into the canal. These canals are orientated longitudinally and radially in between fusiform rays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www4.ncsu.edu/~xylem/WPS202/softwood/swslides/rescan.pdf|title=Resin Canal (also called Resin Duct)|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> They are usually found in late wood: denser wood grown later in the season.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www4.ncsu.edu/~xylem/WPS202/softwood/resin.htm|title=SOFTWOOD ANATOMY...RESIN CANALS|last=Wheeler|first=Elisabeth|date=|website=www4.ncsu.edu|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-10-24}}</ref> [[Resin]] is antiseptic and aromatic and prevents the development of fungi and deters insects.
== Types == * Normal resin canals exist naturally in the wood of the genera [[Spruce|''Picea'']], [[Larch|''Larix'']], [[Pine|''Pinus'']], [[Douglas-fir|''Pseudotsuga'']] and ''[[Shorea]]''. * Traumatic resin canals may be formed in wounded trees that don't have normal resin canals. Wounding occurs from either fire, freezing or mechanical damage. These canals are irregularly shaped compared to normal resin canals.<ref name=":0" />
== Characteristics == Resin canal characteristics (such as number, size and density) in pine species can determine its resistance to pests. In one study, biologists were able to categorize 84% of [[Pinus contorta|lodgepole pine]], and 92% of [[Pinus flexilis|limber pines]], as being either susceptible or resistant to [[bark beetle]]s based only on their resin canals and growth rate over 20 years.<ref>Ferrenberg, S., Kane, J.M. & Mitton, J.B. Oecologia (2014) 174: 1283. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00442-013-2841-2</ref> In another study, scientists found [[Pinus ponderosa|ponderosa pine]] trees that survived drought and bark beetle attacks had resin ducts that were >10% larger in diameter, >25% denser (resin canals per mm<sup>2</sup>), and composed >50% more area of per ring.<ref>Kane, J.M. & Kolb, T.E. Oecologia (2010) 164: 601. https://doi.org/10.1007/s00442-010-1683-4</ref>
== References == {{reflist}}
== Further reading == John G. Haygreen, Jim L. Bowyer: Forest products and wood sciences. Iowa State University Press, Ames, Iowa, 1996 (3rd ed.), {{ISBN|0-8138-2256-4}}
